\begin_layout Subsubsection*
(e) Is there a reason to expect that the additive genetic covariance 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{xy}$
\end_inset

 is large enough to destabilize the evolutionary dynamics of trait and preferenc
e? Would you expect 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{xy}$
\end_inset

 to be positive or negative in a population with sexual selection?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I would expect 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{z}<C_{xy}$
\end_inset

, because (1) the male trait is selected on directly (2) selection decreases
 variance.
